1
00:00:10,977 --> 00:00:14,096
Tonight, 
Richard opens a glove box,

2
00:00:14,097 --> 00:00:16,216
James pulls a face,

3
00:00:16,217 --> 00:00:18,416
and I ask an important question.

4
00:00:18,417 --> 00:00:21,057
Have you ever put
toothpaste on your testicles?

5
00:00:27,297 --> 00:00:29,496
Thank you. Hello. Good evening!

6
00:00:29,497 --> 00:00:31,536
Thank you very much, everybody.

7
00:00:31,537 --> 00:00:34,816
It is a big crowd tonight.

8
00:00:34,817 --> 00:00:37,776
Thanks very much. Thank you. Now...

9
00:00:37,777 --> 00:00:41,376
last year, the big three
German car-makers,

10
00:00:41,377 --> 00:00:44,376
Mercedes, Volkswagen and BMW,

11
00:00:44,377 --> 00:00:47,536
all brought out new hot hatchbacks.

12
00:00:47,537 --> 00:00:50,456
And since this is a top consumer
programme

13
00:00:50,457 --> 00:00:52,736
full of helpful buying advice,

14
00:00:52,737 --> 00:00:57,577
I thought it would be a good idea
to see which one of them is best.

15
00:01:02,697 --> 00:01:06,017
Well, not the Mercedes,
that's for sure.

16
00:01:07,217 --> 00:01:11,897
This is the new four-wheel-drive
A45 and it's extremely powerful...

17
00:01:13,177 --> 00:01:17,176
extremely nice to drive
and handsome as well.

18
00:01:17,177 --> 00:01:19,977
But it is RIDICULOUSLY expensive.

19
00:01:23,017 --> 00:01:27,536
This car, with a few
options on it, is £46,000 and that,

20
00:01:27,537 --> 00:01:30,576
for a hatchback, is idiotic.

21
00:01:30,577 --> 00:01:33,336
It's like charging 100 quid
for a sardine.

22
00:01:33,337 --> 00:01:35,976
"Oh, it is a very good sardine,
sir." I don't care how good it is.

23
00:01:35,977 --> 00:01:37,857
I'm not paying 100 quid for a fish.

24
00:01:39,977 --> 00:01:42,936
If, then, you have even half
a droplet of common sense,

25
00:01:42,937 --> 00:01:47,136
you will be choosing
between these two.

26
00:01:47,137 --> 00:01:49,297
The BMW M135...

27
00:01:50,777 --> 00:01:54,576
and Volkswagen's latest Golf GTI.

28
00:01:54,577 --> 00:01:57,497
Both cost around £30,000.

29
00:01:58,537 --> 00:02:01,617
Both are available with three
or five doors.

30
00:02:02,617 --> 00:02:05,417
Both come as standard
with many things.

31
00:02:07,097 --> 00:02:12,616
And both will be as reliable and as
long-lasting as Edinburgh Castle.

32
00:02:12,617 --> 00:02:15,416
You might think, then,
that they are pretty similar.

33
00:02:15,417 --> 00:02:18,176
But they're not,
which is why I am in the BMW.

34
00:02:18,177 --> 00:02:22,216
You see, the Golf has a two-litre
four-cylinder

35
00:02:22,217 --> 00:02:25,976
turbocharged engine
and that's very nice.

36
00:02:25,977 --> 00:02:32,016
But the BMW has a three-litre
six-cylinder turbocharged engine.

37
00:02:32,017 --> 00:02:34,537
And that's even nicer.

38
00:02:38,337 --> 00:02:40,577
Yes, the Golf is lighter.

39
00:02:41,857 --> 00:02:46,657
But that is not enough to offset
the 90-horsepower disadvantage.

40
00:02:48,217 --> 00:02:51,417
A point I shall now demonstrate
with a small race.

41
00:03:00,857 --> 00:03:03,536
Front-wheel drive Golf is
clinging on jolly well

42
00:03:03,537 --> 00:03:05,817
but frankly, it's pointless.

43
00:03:09,257 --> 00:03:13,297
I can overtake any time I like.
I have the power.

44
00:03:17,097 --> 00:03:21,057
And I have an eight-speed gearbox
compared to his paltry six.

45
00:03:21,977 --> 00:03:24,816
Yes, the Prussian aristocrat

46
00:03:24,817 --> 00:03:28,937
is trampling all over
the lumpen people's car.

47
00:03:34,857 --> 00:03:37,416
There we go. Power!

48
00:03:37,417 --> 00:03:39,057
Come on!

49
00:03:40,177 --> 00:03:42,857
And there we are in front.

50
00:03:45,417 --> 00:03:47,977
'The BMW, then, really is very
fast.'

51
00:03:49,617 --> 00:03:53,616
What's more, because this is
the first hot hatchback

52
00:03:53,617 --> 00:03:58,977
for 30 years to have rear-wheel
drive, you can do this.

53
00:04:06,297 --> 00:04:08,217
Whoo-ha!

54
00:04:09,457 --> 00:04:12,497
'So far, then, the BMW is running
rings round the Golf.

55
00:04:14,297 --> 00:04:17,737
'But I then line them up for
a simple straight-line drag race.

56
00:04:20,897 --> 00:04:23,496
'And there was a problem.

57
00:04:23,497 --> 00:04:25,256
'A big one.'

58
00:04:25,257 --> 00:04:27,136
Three...

59
00:04:27,137 --> 00:04:28,816
two...

60
00:04:28,817 --> 00:04:30,257
one!

61
00:04:38,577 --> 00:04:39,817
Good noise!

62
00:04:44,617 --> 00:04:48,337
With this in reverse...

63
00:04:49,977 --> 00:04:52,616
'At this point,
I was feeling confident.

64
00:04:52,617 --> 00:04:55,017
'But, as I hit 120mph...'

65
00:04:56,017 --> 00:04:57,376
This really is...

66
00:04:57,377 --> 00:04:58,897
Oh, BLEEP BLEEP!

67
00:05:16,537 --> 00:05:20,577
Yeah, you see, the Golf won that
because this, well, it lost control.

68
00:05:21,977 --> 00:05:24,256
That's what happened there.

69
00:05:24,257 --> 00:05:25,697
Whoo!

70
00:05:27,857 --> 00:05:30,617
'After this incident,
I switched to the Golf GTI.

71
00:05:33,377 --> 00:05:38,456
'And I decided immediately it was
a lot better in every single way.

72
00:05:38,457 --> 00:05:41,696
'Not only was it able to travel
in a straight line

73
00:05:41,697 --> 00:05:43,696
'without spinning off..,

74
00:05:43,697 --> 00:05:45,896
'but, thanks to its smaller engine,

75
00:05:45,897 --> 00:05:48,256
'it is a lot more economical
than the BMW.

76
00:05:48,257 --> 00:05:50,856
'And a lot cheaper to insure.'

77
00:05:50,857 --> 00:05:54,296
In fact, because Volkswagen has
fitted this with a forward-facing

78
00:05:54,297 --> 00:05:58,656
radar system that won't let
you have a low-speed crash,

79
00:05:58,657 --> 00:06:05,176
this GTI is in an insurance group
five down from the previous model.

80
00:06:05,177 --> 00:06:09,816
It would be more expensive
to insure a pencil sharpener.

81
00:06:09,817 --> 00:06:12,336
'So the GTI is cheaper to run
and cheaper to buy

82
00:06:12,337 --> 00:06:15,337
'and much better in
a straight line than the BMW.

83
00:06:16,737 --> 00:06:19,937
'But what if you want to transport
a nuclear warhead?'

84
00:06:21,417 --> 00:06:26,136
Well, what we have got here in the
boot of the Volkswagen is a warhead.

85
00:06:26,137 --> 00:06:28,696
And as you can see,
it fits perfectly.

86
00:06:28,697 --> 00:06:35,736
But will it fit in the boot
of the BMW?

87
00:06:35,737 --> 00:06:39,777
Oh, dear. Oh, dearie me.

88
00:06:41,177 --> 00:06:45,176
See, this is the problem really with
rear-wheel drive.

89
00:06:45,177 --> 00:06:46,616
It does rob space.

90
00:06:46,617 --> 00:06:49,136
So you would have to
drive along like that.

91
00:06:49,137 --> 00:06:53,137
And somebody is going to notice.
Hans Blick is, for sure.

92
00:06:54,257 --> 00:06:58,816
'Things are much the same
when it comes to space in the cabin.

93
00:06:58,817 --> 00:07:02,057
'The Golf can handle three
people on the back seat easily.'

94
00:07:03,177 --> 00:07:06,616
But the only way you're going to get
three people in the back

95
00:07:06,617 --> 00:07:10,457
of the BMW is by sawing
their legs off with a hammer.

96
00:07:12,657 --> 00:07:16,176
This is not only
complicated and messy

97
00:07:16,177 --> 00:07:20,856
but, in Britain at least,
it's currently against the law.

98
00:07:20,857 --> 00:07:23,257
Come on! The bone!

99
00:07:28,577 --> 00:07:32,417
One... It's probably easier
to buy the Golf, really.

100
00:07:34,097 --> 00:07:36,416
'So the Golf is cheaper
to buy and cheaper to run

101
00:07:36,417 --> 00:07:39,097
'and also more practical
than the BMW.'

102
00:07:42,257 --> 00:07:45,856
But it's like driving around
in James May's sock drawer.

103
00:07:45,857 --> 00:07:51,016
Everything is exactly where you
would expect it to be. Organised.

104
00:07:51,017 --> 00:07:55,656
Blue ones, brown ones,
pink ones for special occasions.

105
00:07:55,657 --> 00:07:58,456
'Don't think, however,
because it is sensible and practical

106
00:07:58,457 --> 00:08:02,496
'and economical, that it's
in any way boring.' Look.

107
00:08:02,497 --> 00:08:05,496
The gear lever is
a sort of golf ball shape.

108
00:08:05,497 --> 00:08:08,176
You see, you Englishers,
you have the ze Monty Python

109
00:08:08,177 --> 00:08:09,976
and ze Harry and ze Paul

110
00:08:09,977 --> 00:08:13,737
but ve have a sense of humour
also with this. Ja?

111
00:08:15,137 --> 00:08:16,696
'There's more as well.

112
00:08:16,697 --> 00:08:19,576
'Because this particular car
is fitted with Volkswagen's

113
00:08:19,577 --> 00:08:21,217
'optional performance pack.

114
00:08:23,457 --> 00:08:29,536
'That means better brakes,
more power. A top speed of 155mph.

115
00:08:29,537 --> 00:08:32,856
'And a trick front differential.'

116
00:08:32,857 --> 00:08:35,856
Now we have seen clever
front differentials before

117
00:08:35,857 --> 00:08:38,616
but nothing like this.

118
00:08:38,617 --> 00:08:40,656
My foot is hard down now.

119
00:08:40,657 --> 00:08:42,977
Coming round Hammerhead.

120
00:08:45,937 --> 00:08:49,097
And there's no torque steer,
there's no understeer...

121
00:08:52,937 --> 00:08:55,536
You can feel the whole car being
dragged in,

122
00:08:55,537 --> 00:08:57,737
pulled towards the apex.

123
00:08:59,497 --> 00:09:01,497
I've never felt anything like it.

124
00:09:03,777 --> 00:09:07,697
A baboon could get this around here
as fast as the Stig.

125
00:09:16,217 --> 00:09:20,256
'So there we are. These two
cars are not the same at all.

126
00:09:20,257 --> 00:09:23,256
'One is brilliant in every way.

127
00:09:23,257 --> 00:09:25,937
'And the other tried to kill me.'

128
00:09:32,097 --> 00:09:33,936
Very interesting.

129
00:09:33,937 --> 00:09:37,296
Plainly the car to have there.
Oh, yes. Really fascinating.

130
00:09:37,297 --> 00:09:42,176
Just some questions raised.
Let's get this straight.

131
00:09:42,177 --> 00:09:44,016
You don't like the BMW.

132
00:09:44,017 --> 00:09:47,497
Because you can't drive
in a straight line.

133
00:09:48,537 --> 00:09:50,657
Hark who's talking!

134
00:09:51,697 --> 00:09:56,416
How fast did you say you were going?
120mph.

135
00:09:56,417 --> 00:09:58,296
Walking pace, basically.

136
00:09:58,297 --> 00:10:02,696
Listen, from the point where
it suddenly snapped sideways for no

137
00:10:02,697 --> 00:10:05,656
reason, to the point where it
stopped moving, we measured it.

138
00:10:05,657 --> 00:10:07,576
It was over a quarter of a mile.

139
00:10:07,577 --> 00:10:09,536
I could have held it, I reckon.

140
00:10:09,537 --> 00:10:11,856
Could you? You just aquaplaned.

141
00:10:11,857 --> 00:10:14,616
Yes, but the Golf was on the same
track in the same conditions

142
00:10:14,617 --> 00:10:16,616
and it didn't aquaplane.

143
00:10:16,617 --> 00:10:20,057
Now, the Golf didn't aquaplane
because you weren't driving it.

144
00:10:21,417 --> 00:10:24,496
Yes, but, Hammond,
all things considered,

145
00:10:24,497 --> 00:10:28,576
the Golf is a better car.
Is it? It is, honestly.

146
00:10:28,577 --> 00:10:30,336
The diff in it is remarkable.

147
00:10:30,337 --> 00:10:33,296
Because you know when you go round
a corner in a car,

148
00:10:33,297 --> 00:10:35,816
you go like that, yeah?
And it wants to push out.

149
00:10:35,817 --> 00:10:38,856
Well, in this,
the faster you go, it comes in.

150
00:10:38,857 --> 00:10:41,976
It's like Volkswagen has worked out
a way to reverse centrifugal force.

151
00:10:41,977 --> 00:10:45,736
Ah, so Volkswagen have broken
science. Yes. With a diff?

152
00:10:45,737 --> 00:10:47,376
Yes.

153
00:10:47,377 --> 00:10:51,296
And now, we must find out how fast
these cars go round our track.

154
00:10:51,297 --> 00:10:55,296
And that, of course, means handing
them over to our tame racing driver.

155
00:10:55,297 --> 00:11:00,977
Some say that his hair is
the exact same shape as a hat.

156
00:11:03,297 --> 00:11:06,417
And that if he worked for CNN...

157
00:11:09,417 --> 00:11:12,456
..he wouldn't get such pitifully
low ratings

158
00:11:12,457 --> 00:11:14,417
that his show got cancelled.

159
00:11:22,377 --> 00:11:26,216
All we know is he is called
the Stig.

160
00:11:26,217 --> 00:11:27,536
And they're off.

161
00:11:27,537 --> 00:11:30,296
And for the first time this series,
it is actually dry.

162
00:11:30,297 --> 00:11:31,696
First straight.

163
00:11:31,697 --> 00:11:34,736
Will the BMW suddenly
spin off for no reason?

164
00:11:34,737 --> 00:11:37,817
No, it has actually made it
to the first corner. Amazing!

165
00:11:38,937 --> 00:11:42,496
Both turbocharged engines
loving this crisp dry air

166
00:11:42,497 --> 00:11:44,617
and no fuss so far.

167
00:11:50,177 --> 00:11:51,576
No idea what that was.

168
00:11:51,577 --> 00:11:53,816
Right, through Chicago.

169
00:11:53,817 --> 00:11:56,536
Golf's traction control can't be
completely switched off.

170
00:11:56,537 --> 00:11:59,496
You can actually see it
nipping at the brakes on the way in.

171
00:11:59,497 --> 00:12:01,697
The BMW, of course,
just being stupid.

172
00:12:02,817 --> 00:12:05,736
Hammerhead -
no real dramas there either

173
00:12:05,737 --> 00:12:07,136
but the Golf - yes, its magic

174
00:12:07,137 --> 00:12:09,377
differential casually twisting
physics.

175
00:12:14,337 --> 00:12:18,656
Right, Follow Through and yes, the
BMW is trying to spin, of course.

176
00:12:18,657 --> 00:12:21,016
The Golf has a nibble of traction
control and then,

177
00:12:21,017 --> 00:12:22,336
faithful as a Labrador.

178
00:12:22,337 --> 00:12:24,776
Oh, the Golf brake lights flickering
there.

179
00:12:24,777 --> 00:12:27,856
That is the traction control turning
them on, not Stig, who is still

180
00:12:27,857 --> 00:12:32,056
fuming because I said a baboon could
drive as fast in the Golf as him.

181
00:12:32,057 --> 00:12:33,496
Right, just Gambon left.

182
00:12:33,497 --> 00:12:35,456
More hooliganism from the Beemer.

183
00:12:35,457 --> 00:12:36,777
And across the line!

184
00:12:40,657 --> 00:12:42,456
I have the times here.

185
00:12:42,457 --> 00:12:46,016
Come on, then. The BMW...

186
00:12:46,017 --> 00:12:49,856
The BMW went round in 1.25.1

187
00:12:49,857 --> 00:12:52,856
so it is slower than the old
version,

188
00:12:52,857 --> 00:12:55,216
which did it on a damp track.

189
00:12:55,217 --> 00:12:56,776
So that's useless.

190
00:12:56,777 --> 00:12:59,336
And the Golf GTI did a 1.28.6.

191
00:12:59,337 --> 00:13:01,416
Look at that.

192
00:13:01,417 --> 00:13:05,256
That's a lot slower. Yes, yes, yes.
But look. Astra, Megane RS, Focus.

193
00:13:05,257 --> 00:13:08,696
It is right where hot hatchbacks
should be. This is just stupid.

194
00:13:08,697 --> 00:13:12,456
This is much better. And now we must
do the news. Yes, we must.

195
00:13:12,457 --> 00:13:15,216
Which is difficult, because that
means walking over there,

196
00:13:15,217 --> 00:13:18,016
which is a straight line.
You could spin off and lose it.

197
00:13:18,017 --> 00:13:20,856
Thank you, Hammond.
Don't slip. Careful. Here she comes.

198
00:13:20,857 --> 00:13:22,696
Ladies and gentlemen,
will he make it?

199
00:13:22,697 --> 00:13:24,696
Conditions are very
dry in the studio today.

200
00:13:24,697 --> 00:13:28,177
Oh, no, he has only got to step to
go. Shut up. Yes, he has done it.

201
00:13:30,017 --> 00:13:31,856
I thought you were going off.

202
00:13:31,857 --> 00:13:34,016
Listen. It is a tricky
straight, that.

203
00:13:34,017 --> 00:13:39,416
It was easy because my
shoes were not made by BMW. Really.

204
00:13:39,417 --> 00:13:41,096
Good. Now. Do the news now, you two.

205
00:13:41,097 --> 00:13:42,736
The news, ladies and gentlemen.

206
00:13:42,737 --> 00:13:46,576
Now, last week you saw Richard
Hammond driving a six-wheeled

207
00:13:46,577 --> 00:13:49,696
Mercedes-Benz but did you know
they made another six-wheeled

208
00:13:49,697 --> 00:13:52,776
car long before that one? Like
to see a picture of it? Love to.

209
00:13:52,777 --> 00:13:54,576
Here it is.

210
00:13:54,577 --> 00:13:56,416
Oh, right.

211
00:13:56,417 --> 00:13:59,856
Did they not mention this, then?
Do you know, they didn't. How odd.

212
00:13:59,857 --> 00:14:02,136
It is, isn't it,
because Mercedes like to go on

213
00:14:02,137 --> 00:14:05,336
about their heritage and history
and they didn't mention that one.

214
00:14:05,337 --> 00:14:08,416
Well, perhaps they didn't mention it
because it has got Hitler in it.

215
00:14:08,417 --> 00:14:11,736
That is not Hitler. It is. It isn't.

216
00:14:11,737 --> 00:14:14,936
No, that car was built
long before indicators were invented

217
00:14:14,937 --> 00:14:17,176
so he is just the to do some
hand signals.

218
00:14:17,177 --> 00:14:19,496
What signal is he doing here,
then, James?

219
00:14:19,497 --> 00:14:22,537
He's saying, "Take the Third Reich."

220
00:14:30,857 --> 00:14:35,616
Now. Have we got any Scottish
people here? Yes! Yes!

221
00:14:35,617 --> 00:14:39,096
Would you like to step outside just
for the next few minutes? Please.

222
00:14:39,097 --> 00:14:42,216
We've got a bit of a chat.
It's about Scottish independence.

223
00:14:42,217 --> 00:14:44,696
It's just that we've heard
a lot of talk in recent weeks

224
00:14:44,697 --> 00:14:47,776
about what Scotland would lose
if you choose to go on your own

225
00:14:47,777 --> 00:14:50,536
but nobody is talking about what
England would lose.

226
00:14:50,537 --> 00:14:52,816
And it is actually quite a lot.

227
00:14:52,817 --> 00:14:56,176
Because we would lose North Sea oil,
the sub base at Faslane,

228
00:14:56,177 --> 00:15:00,696
all tramps... Oh, God.

229
00:15:00,697 --> 00:15:05,136
And we'd also lose a significant
chunk of our motoring heritage

230
00:15:05,137 --> 00:15:07,456
and I'm not talking
about the Hillmans and Talbots

231
00:15:07,457 --> 00:15:09,936
that were made at the Linwood plant
just outside Paisley.

232
00:15:09,937 --> 00:15:11,896
No, I'm talking about stuff like

233
00:15:11,897 --> 00:15:14,696
the mighty Argyll,
Scotland's finest.

234
00:15:14,697 --> 00:15:16,776
Wow!

235
00:15:16,777 --> 00:15:18,616
Look at that MASTERPIECE!

236
00:15:18,617 --> 00:15:21,616
Do you know, when that car came out,
it was the same price

237
00:15:21,617 --> 00:15:26,056
as a Ferrari 308... Mm.
..and hardly anybody bought one?

238
00:15:26,057 --> 00:15:28,536
Really? It is remarkable
because you look at that...

239
00:15:28,537 --> 00:15:30,736
well, plastic body and you know...

240
00:15:30,737 --> 00:15:32,656
you just look at
the way the door fits.

241
00:15:32,657 --> 00:15:35,616
That is a quality product.
Isn't it? Isn't it? Oh, yeah.

242
00:15:35,617 --> 00:15:38,256
What engine did it have?
Ah, now, it's interesting.

243
00:15:38,257 --> 00:15:42,856
Engine-wise, you could have either
an engine from a Lancia,

244
00:15:42,857 --> 00:15:46,376
a Peugeot, Renault,
you could have a Buick V6...

245
00:15:46,377 --> 00:15:49,616
Basically, it was whatever turned up
in the scrap yard that week.

246
00:15:49,617 --> 00:15:51,376
Basically, yes. Planted in there.

247
00:15:51,377 --> 00:15:54,896
Well, actually, you could also have
it with the option of

248
00:15:54,897 --> 00:15:59,296
a turbocharged Rover V8 and
guess how many of those they sold?

249
00:15:59,297 --> 00:16:03,616
Was it none? Yes, it was none!
Absolutely none at all!

250
00:16:03,617 --> 00:16:06,216
And I have to say,
it wasn't just supercars

251
00:16:06,217 --> 00:16:07,976
where Scotland
was ahead of the game.

252
00:16:07,977 --> 00:16:10,416
They were ahead of the curve, also,
with electric cars

253
00:16:10,417 --> 00:16:13,656
because, way back in the day, they
made a little car called the Scamp.

254
00:16:13,657 --> 00:16:14,936
I've got a picture of it here.

255
00:16:14,937 --> 00:16:17,296
Wow!

256
00:16:17,297 --> 00:16:19,656
Great Scott!

257
00:16:19,657 --> 00:16:22,376
That still has the power to take
your breath away, even today.

258
00:16:22,377 --> 00:16:27,016
It does. Doesn't it just? It's...
It's a rather tragic story, though.

259
00:16:27,017 --> 00:16:29,976
It was made of aluminium and wood
and it was going to be sold

260
00:16:29,977 --> 00:16:33,736
through Electricity Board showrooms,
which I remember, actually.

261
00:16:33,737 --> 00:16:35,936
But when they took it to the
government test centre

262
00:16:35,937 --> 00:16:39,056
to get a road-worthiness certificate
before they could put it on sale,

263
00:16:39,057 --> 00:16:40,936
there was a bit of a problem.

264
00:16:40,937 --> 00:16:44,736
In one test,
the government engineer noted -

265
00:16:44,737 --> 00:16:47,336
and I've written
all the problems, here, down -

266
00:16:47,337 --> 00:16:50,096
"The speedo broke,
the electric motor stopped working,

267
00:16:50,097 --> 00:16:52,856
"the back door flew open,
the spare wheel fell out,

268
00:16:52,857 --> 00:16:56,377
"the steering went wrong
and then the suspension snapped."

269
00:16:58,257 --> 00:17:00,056
And that was the end of that. Aw!

270
00:17:00,057 --> 00:17:02,777
And yet it looked so full of promise,
didn't it, there?

271
00:17:04,497 --> 00:17:07,856
Now, I drove my Mercedes
down to the track this morning

272
00:17:07,857 --> 00:17:10,896
and, genuinely, the most
extraordinary thing happened.

273
00:17:10,897 --> 00:17:12,696
It didn't catch fire.

274
00:17:12,697 --> 00:17:14,096
Really?

275
00:17:14,097 --> 00:17:18,536
Now, James, you came down in your
Fiat Panda, did you not? Yes.

276
00:17:18,537 --> 00:17:21,536
Did that catch fire?
Let me just think. No. Did it not?

277
00:17:21,537 --> 00:17:25,016
No, it didn't at all. Richard, the
hire car you came down in... Yes?!

278
00:17:25,017 --> 00:17:27,456
..did that burst into flames?
No, it didn't. Did it not?

279
00:17:27,457 --> 00:17:29,936
Why are you in a hire car?

280
00:17:29,937 --> 00:17:31,616
Because Porsche have told me

281
00:17:31,617 --> 00:17:35,616
I'm not allowed to drive my brand-new
GT3 and they've taken it off me.

282
00:17:35,617 --> 00:17:39,296
Oh, is this because,
as we mentioned briefly last week,

283
00:17:39,297 --> 00:17:41,416
Porsche GT3s have been
bursting into flames

284
00:17:41,417 --> 00:17:44,096
and now Porsche have told you
you can't drive it any more?

285
00:17:44,097 --> 00:17:46,256
Yes, it is and you both know
full well that it is!

286
00:17:46,257 --> 00:17:48,616
Well, that means you have
no use of those oven gloves,

287
00:17:48,617 --> 00:17:51,136
which I can see down there,
which I bought you last week.

288
00:17:51,137 --> 00:17:52,456
My Porsche driving gloves.

289
00:17:52,457 --> 00:17:56,056
Have they taken it away?
Yes, they've taken it off me!

290
00:17:56,057 --> 00:17:58,256
So, you don't need those,
but it's OK, Hammond,

291
00:17:58,257 --> 00:18:02,096
because I have got you another
present. Oh, good Have you?

292
00:18:02,097 --> 00:18:06,096
No, Hammond, it's a 911 tailored
specifically for you.

293
00:18:06,097 --> 00:18:07,376
Is it

294
00:18:07,377 --> 00:18:09,376
Yes, here it is. Look at that.

295
00:18:09,377 --> 00:18:12,616
Oh, you are literally
the most amusing man

296
00:18:12,617 --> 00:18:15,496
in the whole world. He is.
Even I'm...

297
00:18:15,497 --> 00:18:17,337
Oh, no!

298
00:18:19,057 --> 00:18:23,136
Look! It's OK,
I've got on oven gloves.

299
00:18:23,137 --> 00:18:26,377
Put it out as fast as possible!
It's all right.

300
00:18:29,657 --> 00:18:32,017
I hate you.

301
00:18:35,497 --> 00:18:37,176
Right, now, em...

302
00:18:37,177 --> 00:18:40,176
Yes, as we know, a great many
people in the country

303
00:18:40,177 --> 00:18:42,696
are now starting to use
one of these to move about.

304
00:18:42,697 --> 00:18:44,976
Now, this is called a bicycle

305
00:18:44,977 --> 00:18:49,056
and you can tell just by looking at
it that it is very dangerous

306
00:18:49,057 --> 00:18:51,856
and, as a result,
a lot of people are being hurt

307
00:18:51,857 --> 00:18:53,176
in cycle-related injuries.

308
00:18:53,177 --> 00:18:54,696
In the olden days, the government

309
00:18:54,697 --> 00:18:57,936
would have addressed this problem
by making a public information film.

310
00:18:57,937 --> 00:19:00,256
They used to make them
about all sorts of things.

311
00:19:00,257 --> 00:19:03,576
We had 'Clunk Click Every Trip',
not to go near a railway,

312
00:19:03,577 --> 00:19:05,416
not to play near the water...

313
00:19:05,417 --> 00:19:07,176
Yes, there was 'Don't Run'.

314
00:19:07,177 --> 00:19:10,136
They never told us not to run.
They did! They did not.

315
00:19:10,137 --> 00:19:13,776
I shall show you!
We've got a clip here, look, watch.

316
00:19:13,777 --> 00:19:16,816
'You never know
what's round the corner.

317
00:19:16,817 --> 00:19:18,297
'So don't run.'

318
00:19:19,417 --> 00:19:22,896
There you go. Yes... That's advice
I have heeded all my life.

319
00:19:22,897 --> 00:19:25,736
You really took that to heart!
You haven't run since, have you?

320
00:19:25,737 --> 00:19:28,696
Of course not! There might be
a pane of glass coming!

321
00:19:28,697 --> 00:19:31,776
Anyway, we don't really get these
public information films any more

322
00:19:31,777 --> 00:19:35,016
because of budget cuts and so on,
so Jeremy and I thought,

323
00:19:35,017 --> 00:19:37,376
to help stop cyclists being injured,

324
00:19:37,377 --> 00:19:39,856
it might be a good idea
to bring them back.

325
00:19:39,857 --> 00:19:44,856
So you two are going to make a public
information film about cycling?!

326
00:19:44,857 --> 00:19:46,176
Yes, we are, actually.

327
00:19:46,177 --> 00:19:49,136
We went to see a panel of experts
at London's Westminster Council

328
00:19:49,137 --> 00:19:51,256
and they said
they would be delighted

329
00:19:51,257 --> 00:19:53,296
if we made a public information film

330
00:19:53,297 --> 00:19:55,816
which would help cut
the number of injuries

331
00:19:55,817 --> 00:19:57,296
and this is what...

332
00:19:57,297 --> 00:19:59,337
..I came up with. Here we go.

333
00:20:18,737 --> 00:20:23,337
'John works hard, which means that
he can afford to drive a car.

334
00:20:28,897 --> 00:20:33,136
'That means he gets home
to his family safely every night.'

335
00:20:33,137 --> 00:20:35,097
Daddy's home!

336
00:20:43,177 --> 00:20:44,737
Thank you very much.

337
00:20:46,537 --> 00:20:49,656
I think a work of genius, frankly.

338
00:20:49,657 --> 00:20:53,336
That is terrible. It isn't!
It is! It isn't!

339
00:20:53,337 --> 00:20:57,096
It is. No, it is,
which is why I fired him

340
00:20:57,097 --> 00:21:00,697
and went and had a go at making
a public information film on my own.

341
00:21:04,457 --> 00:21:06,976
'Having come up with
a cracking idea,

342
00:21:06,977 --> 00:21:09,296
'I appointed myself as director,

343
00:21:09,297 --> 00:21:14,016
'gathered together a small cast
and crew, and set to work.'

344
00:21:14,017 --> 00:21:16,376
The whole point of this is...

345
00:21:16,377 --> 00:21:20,096
is to be with you on the swing
and try and look doctor-ish.

346
00:21:20,097 --> 00:21:22,656
That pen isn't very medical,
I'm afraid.

347
00:21:22,657 --> 00:21:24,056
Action.

348
00:21:24,057 --> 00:21:27,496
I love it. Golden! Yeah.

349
00:21:27,497 --> 00:21:29,656
First positions, let's go again.

350
00:21:29,657 --> 00:21:32,936
If you could be opposite each other
on this three-pronged arrangement.

351
00:21:32,937 --> 00:21:35,017
Arms out, singing in the rain.

352
00:21:40,417 --> 00:21:42,376
Good... and action!

353
00:21:42,377 --> 00:21:46,537
Good swinging. Nice.
I'm liking this.

354
00:21:48,177 --> 00:21:52,216
'When my film was finished, Jeremy
and I went to Westminster Council

355
00:21:52,217 --> 00:21:55,176
'to show it to the panel of experts.

356
00:21:55,177 --> 00:22:00,136
'There was Chris Boardman,
policy adviser for British Cycling,

357
00:22:00,137 --> 00:22:03,256
'Martin Low,
City Transport Commissioner

358
00:22:03,257 --> 00:22:07,456
'and Alan Kennedy, Road Safety GB.'

359
00:22:07,457 --> 00:22:11,816
The good news is, we have
two films for you to look at.

360
00:22:11,817 --> 00:22:13,816
No, we have one. No, two.

361
00:22:13,817 --> 00:22:15,176
There's two.

362
00:22:15,177 --> 00:22:17,736
Why don't you show them
yours first of all,

363
00:22:17,737 --> 00:22:20,216
which I believe is that one there?

364
00:22:20,217 --> 00:22:23,296
Gentlemen, if you would like to
relax whilst I just...

365
00:22:23,297 --> 00:22:25,057
insert this in the machine.

366
00:22:36,497 --> 00:22:38,376
Yee-hee-hee! Woo-hoo!

367
00:22:38,377 --> 00:22:39,936
Waaah!

368
00:22:39,937 --> 00:22:44,696
'You stopped playing with
children's toys when you grew up.

369
00:22:44,697 --> 00:22:47,056
'So why ride a bicycle?'

370
00:22:47,057 --> 00:22:50,017
Oh, I did a skid!

371
00:22:58,057 --> 00:23:00,856
You just haven't got it, have you?
Absolutely crazy.

372
00:23:00,857 --> 00:23:03,216
Well, no,
I can see you are disappointed,

373
00:23:03,217 --> 00:23:04,656
just in the way you're looking.

374
00:23:04,657 --> 00:23:07,016
James, they are disappointed
with your work.

375
00:23:07,017 --> 00:23:09,976
May I just play you this one, if I
may. Just let me show you this one

376
00:23:09,977 --> 00:23:12,857
cos I think this will rectify the
problem, which has begun already.

377
00:23:17,177 --> 00:23:21,617
'John works hard, which means that
he can afford to drive a car.

378
00:23:24,537 --> 00:23:26,297
'Work harder. Get a car.'

379
00:23:27,577 --> 00:23:29,776
Terrible. Absolutely terrible.
Sorry, that's...

380
00:23:29,777 --> 00:23:31,936
You just got it wrong, so wrong.
Dreadfully wrong.

381
00:23:31,937 --> 00:23:35,976
Where's the cyclist? Mangled
at the end. What was the brief?

382
00:23:35,977 --> 00:23:39,136
Well, we are trying to
make cycling safer

383
00:23:39,137 --> 00:23:42,296
and we thought the best way to
do that is to stop people cycling.

384
00:23:42,297 --> 00:23:44,616
But the message you should be
getting across

385
00:23:44,617 --> 00:23:47,776
is that people need to
be considerate towards each other.

386
00:23:47,777 --> 00:23:50,416
I'm not sure they are going
to like our poster idea

387
00:23:50,417 --> 00:23:52,937
that we had as well,
but we came up with that.

388
00:23:58,537 --> 00:24:00,176
We did spell it wrong.

389
00:24:00,177 --> 00:24:03,176
I think we are going in entirely
the wrong direction.

390
00:24:03,177 --> 00:24:06,536
Entirely the wrong direction. Have
you actually spoken to a cyclist?

391
00:24:06,537 --> 00:24:07,856
Well, no.

392
00:24:07,857 --> 00:24:11,417
Well, maybe that would be a good
idea, or even try it yourself.

393
00:24:12,977 --> 00:24:15,176
'And so we put on some
cycling clothes

394
00:24:15,177 --> 00:24:17,136
'and went on a fact-finding trip

395
00:24:17,137 --> 00:24:19,457
'around London's
glittering West End.'

396
00:24:21,057 --> 00:24:23,576
Come on, Jeremy! I'm behind you!

397
00:24:23,577 --> 00:24:26,577
I'll sound my bell for pedestrians.

398
00:24:28,497 --> 00:24:31,416
Look at him, he's wearing
normal clothing, the lunatic!

399
00:24:31,417 --> 00:24:35,577
You'll be killed! You're mad!
You will never make it!

400
00:24:37,497 --> 00:24:40,696
Whoo!
I nearly hit that bloke in the face.

401
00:24:40,697 --> 00:24:44,256
'Our mission was to identify
the dangers that cyclists face

402
00:24:44,257 --> 00:24:48,016
'on the city streets
and soon we spotted one.'

403
00:24:48,017 --> 00:24:49,976
James, we've got to go right. Right?

404
00:24:49,977 --> 00:24:54,296
There's a lot of peril involved
in that. Right... Be careful, James.

405
00:24:54,297 --> 00:24:56,736
There is great peril.

406
00:24:56,737 --> 00:24:59,576
'So, we came up with a solution.'

407
00:24:59,577 --> 00:25:01,256
What if we only went left?

408
00:25:01,257 --> 00:25:03,096
That's not a bad idea, actually.

409
00:25:03,097 --> 00:25:05,416
You can still get
where you want to go by going left.

410
00:25:05,417 --> 00:25:07,016
So we go left here, yes?

411
00:25:07,017 --> 00:25:08,097
Yeah.

412
00:25:09,377 --> 00:25:13,056
There is another little left here
we can do. Excellent.

413
00:25:13,057 --> 00:25:17,336
I feel perfectly safe.
I feel completely safe.

414
00:25:17,337 --> 00:25:20,776
No right turns,
that's the main thing with cycling.

415
00:25:20,777 --> 00:25:24,176
I reckon it improves your chances
of survival by about 85%.

416
00:25:24,177 --> 00:25:25,456
Definitely.

417
00:25:25,457 --> 00:25:28,376
Oh, hang on.
No, I'm not sure that has worked.

418
00:25:28,377 --> 00:25:32,337
I've seen Charles Saatchi having
lunch five times already.

419
00:25:34,137 --> 00:25:35,816
'After an hour in the saddle,

420
00:25:35,817 --> 00:25:38,696
'I discovered
another problem for cyclists.'

421
00:25:38,697 --> 00:25:41,936
Oh, bump, bump!

422
00:25:41,937 --> 00:25:45,137
Really bumpy here and
this is deeply uncomfortable now.

423
00:25:46,577 --> 00:25:48,257
Oh!

424
00:25:49,417 --> 00:25:51,776
Oof! Ow!

425
00:25:51,777 --> 00:25:55,056
I've got to do something
about my bottom, this is really...

426
00:25:55,057 --> 00:25:57,377
uncomfortable.

427
00:25:58,817 --> 00:26:00,576
'So we stopped at a bicycle shop

428
00:26:00,577 --> 00:26:03,376
'where, apparently,
you can buy special creams.'

429
00:26:03,377 --> 00:26:07,256
Are these all to rub onto your bits?
Yes, they are.

430
00:26:07,257 --> 00:26:09,576
Is that normal? Yes,
we even have one for women.

431
00:26:09,577 --> 00:26:12,456
Are women's bottoms different to
men's bottoms? I should think so.

432
00:26:12,457 --> 00:26:13,536
Are they? Yes.

433
00:26:13,537 --> 00:26:15,536
'Having selected the correct cream,

434
00:26:15,537 --> 00:26:18,737
'I went to apply it
in the changing room.'

435
00:26:27,457 --> 00:26:29,136
'This made everything worse.'

436
00:26:29,137 --> 00:26:30,816
Ooh!

437
00:26:30,817 --> 00:26:34,256
Have you ever put toothpaste
on your testicles for a joke?

438
00:26:34,257 --> 00:26:36,336
To be honest, yes, I did,
when I was a teenager.

439
00:26:36,337 --> 00:26:39,136
Yes, exactly, so did I.
Do you remember the pain? Yes, I do.

440
00:26:39,137 --> 00:26:41,457
Well... Is that what it's like?

441
00:26:42,697 --> 00:26:44,776
'James was very sympathetic.'

442
00:26:44,777 --> 00:26:47,536
♪ Goodness gracious
great balls of fire! ♪

443
00:26:47,537 --> 00:26:52,976
'With the pain getting worse...'
Ooh! Ow! Ow!

444
00:26:52,977 --> 00:26:55,536
'..I had to make an emergency stop.'

445
00:26:55,537 --> 00:26:59,656
Please may I use your lavatories?
My scrotum is on fire.

446
00:26:59,657 --> 00:27:01,976
Have you ever put toothpaste
on your scrotum?

447
00:27:01,977 --> 00:27:03,497
Ooh...

448
00:27:04,737 --> 00:27:08,496
'With my gentleman's area sorted,
we got back on the road.'

449
00:27:08,497 --> 00:27:11,296
Right, so the light just went red,

450
00:27:11,297 --> 00:27:13,656
so that means go
when you're on a bicycle.

451
00:27:13,657 --> 00:27:17,376
'And soon we were picking up
valuable information.'

452
00:27:17,377 --> 00:27:21,216
Taxi driver. Very polite. Thank
you very much, sir. Another taxi.

453
00:27:21,217 --> 00:27:23,816
Extremely polite.

454
00:27:23,817 --> 00:27:25,856
Thank you.

455
00:27:25,857 --> 00:27:28,536
Yeah, look at that, you see,
he politely let me go.

456
00:27:28,537 --> 00:27:30,177
Thank you.

457
00:27:31,537 --> 00:27:34,136
I've been riding now for three hours

458
00:27:34,137 --> 00:27:38,136
and not a single car driver
has done anything annoying.

459
00:27:38,137 --> 00:27:41,736
You'd imagine that cycling
around Hyde Park Corner,

460
00:27:41,737 --> 00:27:44,136
which is what I'm doing now,
would be...

461
00:27:44,137 --> 00:27:46,616
as dangerous as juggling chain saws,

462
00:27:46,617 --> 00:27:50,576
but if you keep your eyes open
and you are courteous...

463
00:27:50,577 --> 00:27:52,697
it's fine.

464
00:27:54,177 --> 00:27:57,256
Every car has given me a
six-foot berth, taxis, vans.

465
00:27:57,257 --> 00:27:59,696
Yes, all the cars
and vans have been very decent.

466
00:27:59,697 --> 00:28:01,576
I haven't got a complaint.

467
00:28:01,577 --> 00:28:06,056
'But... there was one type of road
user who wasn't courteous at all.'

468
00:28:06,057 --> 00:28:07,737
Look at this idiot!

469
00:28:12,097 --> 00:28:14,816
Whoa! God above!

470
00:28:14,817 --> 00:28:16,816
So that bus just overtook me,

471
00:28:16,817 --> 00:28:20,456
so I have to now go on the wrong
side of the road and you get...

472
00:28:20,457 --> 00:28:23,416
And now he's just set off! See?

473
00:28:23,417 --> 00:28:27,136
And I'm stuck
on the wrong side of the road.

474
00:28:27,137 --> 00:28:31,536
These are the problem, I've decided.
The buses.

475
00:28:31,537 --> 00:28:33,336
Because all of the drivers think

476
00:28:33,337 --> 00:28:36,417
they are literally
Lord God Almighty.

477
00:28:39,537 --> 00:28:43,056
It's bloody murder!
Now they're giving me a wide berth.

478
00:28:43,057 --> 00:28:46,176
Your bus is going to kill me!

479
00:28:46,177 --> 00:28:48,376
You are going to kill me!
